oad to Manga\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type         = tv series\n| title        = The Seven Deadly Sins: Signs of Holy War\n| director     = [[Tomokazu Tokoro]]\n| producer     = \n| writer       = {{Unbulleted list|Nakaba Suzuki|Yuniko Ayana|Yuichiro Kido}}\n| music        = {{Unbulleted list|Hiroyuki Sawano|Takafumi Wada}}\n| studio       = A-1 Pictures\n| licensee     = Netflix {{small|(streaming rights)}}\n| network      = JNN (MBS, TBS)\n| network_en   = {{English anime network|SEA=Animax Asia}}\n| first        = August 28, 2016\n| last         = September 18, 2016\n| episodes     = 4\n| episode_list = The Seven Deadly Sins: Signs of Holy War\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| title           = The Seven Deadly Sins: Seven Days ~The Thief and the Holy Girl~\n| type            = manga\n| author          = Y\u014d Kokukuji\n| publisher       = Kodansha\n| publisher_en    = \n| demographic     = ''Sh\u014dnen''\n| imprint         = \n| magazine        = Sh\u014dnen Magazine Edge\n| magazine_en     = \n| first           = January 17, 2017\n| last            = August 17, 2017\n| volumes         = 2\n| volume_list     = List of The Seven Deadly Sins chapters#The Seven Deadly Sins: Seven Days ~The Thief and the Holy Girl~\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| title           = The Seven Deadly Sins: Revival of The Commandments\n| director        = Takeshi Furuta\n| producer        = \n| writer          = Takao Yoshioka\n| music           = {{Unbulleted list|Hiroyuki Sawano|Kohta Yamamoto|Takafumi Wada}}\n| studio          = A-1 Pictures\n| licensee        = Netflix {{small|(streaming rights)}}\n| network         = JNN (MBS, TBS)\n| network_en      = {{English anime network|SEA=Animax Asia}}\n| first           = January 13, 2018\n| last            = June 30, 2018\n| episodes        = 24 + OVA\n| episode_list    = The Seven Deadly Sins: Revival of The Commandments\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Other\n| title           = Film\n| content         =\n* ''[[The Seven Deadly Sins the Movie: Prisoners of the Sky]]''\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| title           = The Seven Deadly Sins: Wrath of the Gods\n| director        = Susumu Nishizawa\n| producer        = \n| writer          = Rintar\u014d Ikeda\n| music           = {{Unbulleted list|Hiroyuki Sawano|Kohta Yamamoto|Takafumi Wada}}\n| studio          = [[Studio Deen]]\n| licensee        = Netflix {{small|(streaming rights)}}<ref>{{cite tweet |user=NXOnNetflix |number=1237755158672490497 |date= 11 March 2020 |title=Meliodas and crew face their greatest challenge yet when hit fantasy anime The Seven Deadly Sins returns! The Seven Deadly Sins: Wrath of the Gods arrives this July. }}</ref>\n| network         = [[TV Tokyo]], [[TX Network|BS-TX]]\n| network_en      = {{English anime network|SEA=Animax Asia}}\n| first           = October 9, 2019\n| last            = March 25, 2020\n| episodes        = 24\n| episode_list    = The Seven Deadly Sins: Wrath of the Gods\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type            = tv series\n| title           = The Seven Deadly Sins: Anger's Judgement\n| director        = \n| producer        = \n| writer          =\n| music           = \n| studio          = \n| licensee        = \n| network         = TV Tokyo, BS-TX\n| network_en      = \n| first           = October 2020\n| last            = scheduled\n| episodes        = \n| episode_list    =\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''The Seven Deadly Sins'''''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a|Nanatsu no Taizai|lead=yes}} is a Japanese fantasy [[manga]] series written and illustrated by [[Nakaba Suzuki]]. It has been serialized in [[Kodansha]]'s ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine]]'' since October 2012, with the chapters collected into forty ''[[tank\u014dbon]]'' volumes as of September 17, 2019. The manga features a setting similar to the [[History of Europe#Middle Ages|European Middle Ages]], with its titular group of knights representing the [[seven deadly sins]].\n\nThe series was adapted into an [[anime]] television series that ran for three seasons by [[A-1 Pictures]] and [[Studio Deen]]. A film titled ''[[The Seven Deadly Sins the Movie: Prisoners of the Sky]]'' premiered in August 18, 2018.\n\nThe manga has been licensed by [[Kodansha USA]] for English publication in North America, while the chapters are released digitally by [[Crunchyroll]] in over 170 countries as they are published in Japan. [[Netflix]] acquired the exclusive English streaming rights for the anime series while [[Funimation]] currently has the home video rights.\n\nAs of December 2018, ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' had over 30 million copies in circulation. The manga won the 39th [[Kodansha Manga Award]] for the ''sh\u014dnen'' category in 2015.\n\n{{TOClimit|limit=3}}\n\nP\n\n==Media==\n===Manga===\n{{main|List of The Seven Deadly Sins chapters}}\nWritten and illustrated by [[Nakaba Suzuki]], ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' began as a [[One-shot (comics)|one-shot]] pilot chapter published on November 22, 2011 in ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine]]'''s 52 issue of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/magazine/index.php/02065/newest/1508|title=No.52 2011\u5e7411\u670822\u65e5\uff08\u706b\uff09\u767a\u58f2|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2013-11-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131110050924/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/magazine/index.php/02065/newest/1508|archivedate=November 10, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The manga started serialization in the magazine's 45 issue of 2012, released on October 10, 2012. The chapters have been collected into 40 ''[[tank\u014dbon]]'' volumes as of February 17, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?item=0000328011|script-title=ja:\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\uff08\uff14\uff10\uff09|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref> The first of three planned story arcs was completed with chapter 100 and Suzuki has originally projected that the series would run for 20 to 30 volumes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-19/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-1st-of-3-planned-arcs-ends/.83434 |title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga's 1st of 3 Planned Arcs Ends |website=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2015-01-19 |accessdate=2015-01-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119110059/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-19/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-1st-of-3-planned-arcs-ends/.83434 |archive-date=January 19, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The series is licensed for English language release in North America by [[Kodansha USA]], who published the first volume on March 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-10-11/kodansha-comics-adds-uq-holder-seven-deadly-sins-manga|title=Kodansha Comics Adds UQ Holder, Seven Deadly Sins Manga|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-10-11|accessdate=2013-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110095441/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-10-11/kodansha-comics-adds-uq-holder-seven-deadly-sins-manga|archive-date=November 10, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1612629210/ |title=The Seven Deadly Sins Volume 1|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=2013-11-04}}</ref> In February 2020, Suzuki posted on his [[Twitter]] account that the manga has \"one more volume left\" after volume 40.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Antonio Pineda |first1=Rafael |title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga Creator: There Is 1 More Volume Left |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-13/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-creator-there-is-1-more-volume-left/.156442 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=February 14, 2020 |date=February 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200214053141/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-13/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-creator-there-is-1-more-volume-left/.156442 |archive-date=February 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Suzuki has mentioned in an afterword that side stories are also planned for based on the remaining characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-17/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-ends-with-41st-volume-in-may/.156526|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga Ends With 41st Volume in May|website=Anime News Network|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217070944/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-02-17/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-ends-with-41st-volume-in-may/.156526|archive-date=February 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The manga will be finished on March 25, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Jennifer |title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga Ends on March 25 |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2020-03-17/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-ends-on-march-25/.157598 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317171809/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2020-03-17/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-ends-on-march-25/.157598 |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As the series is published in Japan, it is also released simultaneously in English digitally by [[Crunchyroll]] in over 170 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-press-release/2013/10/30-1/crunchyroll-launches-crunchyroll-manga-digital-comic-platform|title=CRUNCHYROLL LAUNCHES \"CRUNCHYROLL MANGA\" DIGITAL COMIC PLATFORM|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=2013-10-30|accessdate=2013-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105133919/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-press-release/2013/10/30-1/crunchyroll-launches-crunchyroll-manga-digital-comic-platform|archive-date=November 5, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-10-26/crunchyroll-to-simultaneously-offer-kodansha-manga-in-170-countries|title=Crunchyroll to Simultaneously Offer Kodansha Manga in 170 Countries|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-10-26|accessdate=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031065854/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-10-26/crunchyroll-to-simultaneously-offer-kodansha-manga-in-170-countries|archive-date=October 31, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA special issue of ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine'', published on October 19, 2013, featured a small crossover between ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' and [[Hiro Mashima]]'s ''[[Fairy Tail]]'', where each artist drew a ''[[yonkoma]]'' (four-panel comic) of the other's series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/comic/news/101712|title=\u9234\u6728\u592e\u304c\u300cFAIRY TAIL\u300d\u3001\u771f\u5cf6\u30d2\u30ed\u304c\u300c\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u300d\u3092\u57f7\u7b46|language=Japanese|publisher=Natalie|date=2013-10-19|accessdate=2013-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021131111/http://natalie.mu/comic/news/101712|archive-date=October 21, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> An actual crossover chapter between the two ran in the magazine's combined 4/5 issue of 2014, which was released on December 25, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-12-06/fairy-tail-the-seven-deadly-sins-get-crossover-1-shot-manga|title=Fairy Tail, The Seven Deadly Sins Get Crossover 1-Shot Manga|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-12-06|accessdate=2013-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208101858/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-12-06/fairy-tail-the-seven-deadly-sins-get-crossover-1-shot-manga|archive-date=December 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Nakaba wrote a one-shot for the November 2014 issue of the [[sh\u014djo manga|''sh\u014djo'' manga]] magazine ''[[Nakayoshi]]'', released on October 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-09-03/the-seven-deadly-sins-gets-one-shot-in-nakayoshi-magazine-for-girls/.78342|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Gets One-Shot in Nakayoshi Magazine For Girls|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-09-03|accessdate=2014-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904031006/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-09-03/the-seven-deadly-sins-gets-one-shot-in-nakayoshi-magazine-for-girls/.78342|archive-date=September 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He also created a comedic one-shot depicting how Meliodas and Hawk first met that ran in the October 20, 2014 issue of ''[[Magazine Special]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-09-20/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-comedy-1-shot-story/.79013|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga Gets Comedy 1-Shot Story|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-09-20|accessdate=2014-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922022256/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-09-20/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-comedy-1-shot-story/.79013|archive-date=September 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> From February 24 to May 10, 2015, two more spin-off manga by Nakaba were available on the smartphone and tablet application ''[[Manga Box]]''. {{nihongo|''Naku na, Tomo yo''|\u6ce3\u304f\u306a \u53cb\u3088||\"Do Not Cry, My Friend\"}} is about Hendrickson and Dreyfus' younger years, while {{nihongo|''Gilthunder no Shinjitsu''|\u30ae\u30eb\u30b5\u30f3\u30c0\u30fc\u306e\u771f\u5b9f||\"Gilthunder's Truth\"}} is set after the Vaizel Fight Festival arc and follows Gilthunder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-02-26/the-seven-deadly-sins-2nd-new-spinoff-manga-by-creator-posted/.85392|title=The Seven Deadly Sins' 2nd New Spinoff Manga by Creator Posted|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-02-26|accessdate=2015-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150226164004/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-02-26/the-seven-deadly-sins-2nd-new-spinoff-manga-by-creator-posted/.85392|archive-date=February 26, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> An original 40-page manga by [[Nakaba Suzuki]] will be distributed during screenings of ''The Seven Deadly Sins the Movie: Prisoners of the Sky'' movie.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|url=https://manga.tokyo/news/seven-deadly-sins-prisoner-of-the-sky-reveals-present-for-cinema-goers/|title=Seven Deadly Sins \u2013 Prisoner of the Sky Reveals Present for Cinema Goers|date=July 2, 2018|website=[[MANGA.TOKYO]]|accessdate=July 2, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702175647/https://manga.tokyo/news/seven-deadly-sins-prisoner-of-the-sky-reveals-present-for-cinema-goers/|archive-date=July 2, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Spin-off manga====\n{{main|List of The Seven Deadly Sins chapters#Spin-offs}}\nA comedic spin-off series by Juichi Yamaki, titled {{nihongo|''Mayoe! The Seven Deadly Sins Academy!''|\u8ff7\u3048\uff01\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u5b66\u5712\uff01|Mayoe! Nanatsu no Taizai Gakuen!}} and imagining the characters as high school students, ran in ''[[Bessatsu Sh\u014dnen Magazine]]'' from August 9, 2014 to October 8, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-29/the-seven-deadly-sins-gets-school-comedy-manga-spinoff/.76095|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Gets School Comedy Manga Spinoff|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-06-29|accessdate=2014-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630220013/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-29/the-seven-deadly-sins-gets-school-comedy-manga-spinoff/.76095|archive-date=June 30, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-10-09/the-seven-deadly-sins-spinoff-manga-mayoe-nanatsu-no-taizai-gakuen-ends/.107438|title=The Seven Deadly Sins' Spinoff Manga Mayoe! Nanatsu no Taizai Gakuen! Ends|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2016-10-09|accessdate=2016-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010174847/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-10-09/the-seven-deadly-sins-spinoff-manga-mayoe-nanatsu-no-taizai-gakuen-ends/.107438|archive-date=October 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> It was collected into four ''tank\u014dbon'' volumes. {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins Production''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u30d7\u30ed\u30c0\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3|Nanatsu no Taizai Purodakushon}}, a comedic spin-off by Chiemi Sakamoto that imagines the characters as actors performing in a live-action TV show, ran in ''[[Aria (magazine)|Aria]]'' from November 28, 2015 to October 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2015/11/28-1/seven-deadly-sins-inspires-shoujo-parody-spin-off|title=\"Seven Deadly Sins\" Inspires Shoujo Parody Spin-Off|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=2015-11-28|accessdate=2015-12-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208152509/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2015/11/28-1/seven-deadly-sins-inspires-shoujo-parody-spin-off|archive-date=December 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-09-29/seven-deadly-sins-production-manga-reaches-climax-in-october/.122026|title=Seven Deadly Sins Production Manga Reaches 'Climax' in October|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=2017-09-29|accessdate=2018-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205130132/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-09-29/seven-deadly-sins-production-manga-reaches-climax-in-october/.122026|archive-date=February 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was collected into four ''tank\u014dbon'' volumes.\n\nA comedic ''yonkoma'' titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: King's Road to Manga''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\u306e\u6f2b\u753b\u9053|Nanatsu no Taizai Kingu no Manga Michi}} and written by Masataka Ono that depicts King as an aspiring manga artist, began on February 20, 2016 in ''Magazine Special'' before transferring to the ''Manga Box'' app on February 1, 2017 and ending later that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-01-19/seven-deadly-sins-4-panel-spinoff-reimagines-king-as-aspiring-manga-creator/.97731|title=Seven Deadly Sins' 4-Panel Spinoff Reimagines King as Aspiring Manga Creator|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2016-01-19|accessdate=2016-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160120193845/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-01-19/seven-deadly-sins-4-panel-spinoff-reimagines-king-as-aspiring-manga-creator/.97731|archive-date=January 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-16/seven-deadly-sins-spinoff-manga-king-no-manga-michi-ends-with-3rd-volume/.117605|title=Seven Deadly Sins Spinoff Manga King no Manga Michi Ends With 3rd Volume|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2017-06-16|accessdate=2018-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205185953/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-16/seven-deadly-sins-spinoff-manga-king-no-manga-michi-ends-with-3rd-volume/.117605|archive-date=February 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Its chapters were collected into three ''tank\u014dbon'' volumes. A manga adaptation of Mamoru Iwasa's novel ''Seven Days'' was serialized in ''Sh\u014dnen Magazine Edge'' from January 17 to September 2017 and shows how Ban and Elaine met in more detail. It is illustrated by Y\u014d Kokukuji, titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Seven Days ~The Thief and the Holy Girl~''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u30bb\u30d6\u30f3\u30c7\u30a4\u30ba\uff5e\u76d7\u8cca\u3068\u8056\u5c11\u5973\uff5e|Nanatsu no Taizai: Sebun Deizu ~T\u014dzoku to Seish\u014djo~}} and was collected into two ''tank\u014dbon'' volumes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-18/seven-deadly-sins-spinoff-manga-about-ban-and-elaine-ends-in-september/.120213|title=Seven Deadly Sins Spinoff Manga About Ban & Elaine Ends in September|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2017-08-18|accessdate=2018-02-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205184334/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-08-18/seven-deadly-sins-spinoff-manga-about-ban-and-elaine-ends-in-september/.120213|archive-date=February 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anime===\n{{see also|List of The Seven Deadly Sins episodes}}\nIn April 2014, the 20th issue of ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine'' announced that ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' was being adapted into an anime television series.<ref name=\"3 million\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-04-11/the-seven-deadly-sins-fantasy-manga-gets-tv-anime|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Fantasy Manga Gets TV Anime|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-04-11|accessdate=2014-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413002655/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-04-11/the-seven-deadly-sins-fantasy-manga-gets-tv-anime|archive-date=April 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/comic/news/114525|title=\u300c\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u300dTV\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u5316\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01\u5358\u884c\u672c\u306f\u7d2f\u8a08300\u4e07\u90e8\u7a81\u7834|language=Japanese|publisher=Natalie|date=2014-04-16|accessdate=2014-07-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416094701/http://natalie.mu/comic/news/114525|archive-date=April 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The series debuted on [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]] and other [[Japan News Network]] stations on October 5, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/comic/news/122126|script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u300c\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u300d10\u6708\u3088\u308a\u65e55\u67a0\u3067\u653e\u9001|language=Japanese|publisher=Natalie|date=2014-07-27|accessdate=2014-07-27|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729223821/http://natalie.mu/comic/news/122126|archive-date=July 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"airdate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-07-27/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-commercial-streamed/.77056|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Anime Commercial Streamed|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-07-27|accessdate=2014-07-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140801213236/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-07-27/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-commercial-streamed/.77056|archive-date=August 1, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The staff was revealed in the combined 36/37 issue of the year: created by [[A-1 Pictures]], directed by [[Tensai Okamura]], written by Sh\u014dtar\u014d Suga (''[[Lagrange: The Flower of Rin-ne]]''), with Keigo Sasaki (''[[Blue Exorcist]]'') providing character designs and [[Hiroyuki Sawano]] composing the music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-08-01/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-game-cast-staff-announced/.77198|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Anime's Game, Cast, Staff Announced|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-08-01|accessdate=2014-08-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803204457/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-08-01/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-game-cast-staff-announced/.77198|archive-date=August 3, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The show's first opening theme song is {{nihongo4|\"Netsuj\u014d no Spectrum\"|\u71b1\u60c5\u306e\u30b9\u30da\u30af\u30c8\u30e9\u30e0|Netsuj\u014d no Supekutoramu|\"Spectrum of Passion\"}} performed by [[Ikimono-gakari]] for the first twelve episodes and the second opening theme is \"Seven Deadly Sins\" performed by [[Man with a Mission]], while the first ending theme titled \"7-Seven\" is a collaboration between [[Flow (Japanese band)|Flow]] and [[Granrodeo]], the second ending theme from episode thirteen onwards is \"Season\" the major label debut of [[Alisa Takigawa]].<ref name=\"5 million\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-08-12/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-theme-songs-game-detailed/.77548|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Anime's Theme Songs, Game Detailed|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-08-12|accessdate=2014-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812210614/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-08-12/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-theme-songs-game-detailed/.77548|archive-date=August 12, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-12-21/man-with-a-mission-alisa-takigawa-perform-the-seven-deadly-sins-new-songs/.82460|title=Man With A Mission, Alisa Takigawa Perform The Seven Deadly Sins' New Songs|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-12-21|accessdate=2015-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225061112/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-12-21/man-with-a-mission-alisa-takigawa-perform-the-seven-deadly-sins-new-songs/.82460|archive-date=December 25, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA second anime series was confirmed on September 27, 2015 to air in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-09-27/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-new-tv-anime-in-2016/.93443|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga Gets New TV Anime in 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-09-29|accessdate=2015-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929183034/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-09-27/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-new-tv-anime-in-2016/.93443|archive-date=September 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> This turned out to be a four-week anime television special featuring an original story by Nakaba Suzuki, titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Signs of Holy War''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u8056\u6226\u306e\u4e88\u5146|Nanatsu no Taizai: Seisen no Shirushi}}, that began airing on August 28, 2016 on [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]] and [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-05-10/the-seven-deadly-sins-signs-of-holy-war-4-episode-special-premieres-on-august-28/.101919|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Signs of holy war 4-Episode Special Premieres on August 28|date=2016-05-10|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=2016-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511120115/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-05-10/the-seven-deadly-sins-signs-of-holy-war-4-episode-special-premieres-on-august-28/.101919|archive-date=May 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The special was produced by A-1 Pictures, directed by [[Tomokazu Tokoro]], and written by Yuniko Ayana and Yuichiro Kido, featuring character designs by Keigo Sasaki. The music was composed by Hiroyuki Sawano and Takafumi Wada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-27/seven-deadly-sins-gets-4-week-tv-anime-special-in-august-with-brand-new-story/.100352|title=Seven Deadly Sins Gets 4-Week TV Anime Special In August With Brand-New Story|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2016-03-27|accessdate=2016-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328165239/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-27/seven-deadly-sins-gets-4-week-tv-anime-special-in-august-with-brand-new-story/.100352|archive-date=March 28, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Its opening theme song is \"Classic\" by the rock band [[Mucc]] and its ending theme is {{nihongo|\"Iroasenai Hitomi\"|\u8272\u892a\u305b\u306a\u3044\u77b3}} by Alisa Takigawa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-08-09/the-seven-deadly-sins-signs-of-holy-war-tv-special-ad-previews-opening-theme-song/.105170|title=The Seven Deadly Sins -Signs of Holy War- TV Special's Ad Previews Opening Theme Song|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2016-08-09|accessdate=2017-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227062634/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-08-09/the-seven-deadly-sins-signs-of-holy-war-tv-special-ad-previews-opening-theme-song/.105170|archive-date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A commercial following the final episode confirmed a second anime series has been green-lit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-09-18/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-next-tv-anime-series-teases-new-adventures-in-ad/.106606|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga's Next TV Anime Series Teases New Adventures in Ad|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2016-09-18|accessdate=2017-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227062645/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-09-18/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-next-tv-anime-series-teases-new-adventures-in-ad/.106606|archive-date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe first ''Seven Deadly Sins'' anime series was licensed for English release by [[Netflix]] as its second exclusive anime, following their acquisition of ''[[Knights of Sidonia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hnewman/2015/10/09/netflix-to-announce-its-second-exclusive-anime-series-tomorrow/|title=Netflix To Announce Its Second Exclusive Anime Series Tomorrow: 'The Seven Deadly Sins'|last=Newman|first=Heather|website=[[Forbes]]|date=2015-10-09|accessdate=2015-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170918065205/https://www.forbes.com/sites/hnewman/2015/10/09/netflix-to-announce-its-second-exclusive-anime-series-tomorrow/|archive-date=September 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> All 24 episodes were released on November 1, 2015 in both subtitled or English dub formats. The ''Signs of Holy War'' arc, labeled as \"Season 2\", has also been licensed by Netflix and was released on February 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-25/netflix-to-stream-the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-season-2-in-february/.111482|title=Netflix to Stream The Seven Deadly Sins Anime's 'Season 2' in February|date=January 26, 2017|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=January 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128080205/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-25/netflix-to-stream-the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-season-2-in-february/.111482|archive-date=January 28, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On February 14, 2017, [[Funimation]] announced that they acquired the first anime for home video distribution for US and Canada and released the series on Blu-ray and DVD later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-02-14/funimation-acquires-home-video-rights-for-seven-deadly-sins/.112236|title=Funimation Acquires Home Video Rights for Seven Deadly Sins|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 14, 2017|accessdate=February 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215113417/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-02-14/funimation-acquires-home-video-rights-for-seven-deadly-sins/.112236|archive-date=February 15, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Part One of the first season was released on Blu-Ray on May 15th, 2017 with Part Two being released June 20th the same year.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Part One Blu-ray|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Part-One-Blu-ray/173867/|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215223230/https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Part-One-Blu-ray/173867/|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Part Two Blu-ray|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Part-Two-Blu-ray/175898/|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215224130/https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Part-Two-Blu-ray/175898/|archive-date=December 15, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The complete entirety of the first season was released on August 14th, 2018.<ref>{{Citation|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Season One Blu-ray|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Season-One-Blu-ray/206023/|access-date=2018-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180905024712/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Season-One-Blu-ray/206023/|archive-date=September 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Madman Entertainment]] is importing Funimation's release into Australia and New Zealand, with a release scheduled for January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://b2b.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=46267|title=Seven Deadly Sins Season 1 (Eps 1-24) (Blu-Ray)|publisher=[[Madman Entertainment]]|accessdate=October 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA second season, titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Revival of The Commandments''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u6212\u3081\u306e\u5fa9\u6d3b|Nanatsu no Taizai: Imashime no Fukkatsu}}, was announced at the \"Nanatsu no Taizai FES\" event in July 2017 and premiered on January 13, 2018. Takeshi Furuta and Takao Yoshioka replaced Tensai Okamura and Sh\u014dtar\u014d Suga as director and series composer, respectively, while the other main staff members returned from the first season to reprise their roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-07-16/seven-deadly-sins-anime-reveals-new-season-january-2018-premiere-title-cast-staff-visual-trailer/.118900|title=Seven Deadly Sins Anime Reveals New Season's January 2018 Premiere, Title, Cast, Staff, Visual, Trailer|date=July 16, 2017|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=July 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718121939/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-07-16/seven-deadly-sins-anime-reveals-new-season-january-2018-premiere-title-cast-staff-visual-trailer/.118900|archive-date=July 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Revival of the Commandments'' arc, labeled as \"Season 3\", was released on October 15, 2018 on Netflix.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-26/netflix-u.s-sets-violet-evergarden-special-episode-seven-deadly-sins-season-2-premiere-dates-for-october/.137326|title=Netflix U.S. Sets Violet Evergarden Special Episode, Seven Deadly Sins Season 2 Premiere Dates for October|last=Ressler|first=Karen|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2018-09-26|accessdate=2018-09-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928021836/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-26/netflix-u.s-sets-violet-evergarden-special-episode-seven-deadly-sins-season-2-premiere-dates-for-october/.137326|archive-date=September 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>  The first opening theme song of the series titled \"Howling\" is a collaboration between Flow and Granrodeo, and first ending theme song is \"Beautiful\" performed by Anly. The second opening theme titled \"Ame ga Furu kara, Niji ga Deru\"(\u96e8\u304c\u964d\u308b\u304b\u3089\u8679\u304c\u51fa\u308b) by Sky Peace and second ending theme titled \"Chikai\"(\u8a93\u3044) by [[Sora Amamiya]].\n\nA third season, titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Wrath of the Gods''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u795e\u3005\u306e\u9006\u9c57|Nanatsu no Taizai: Kamigami no Gekirin}} premiered on October 9, 2019 on [[TV Tokyo]] and [[TX Network|BS TV Tokyo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=New Seven Deadly Sins TV Anime Premieres on October 9 |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2019-09-06/new-seven-deadly-sins-tv-anime-premieres-on-october-9/.150808 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=September 6, 2019 |date=September 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190906144721/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2019-09-06/new-seven-deadly-sins-tv-anime-premieres-on-october-9/.150808 |archive-date=September 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Chapman |first1=Paul |title=Heroes and Villains Clash in The Seven Deadly Sins: Wrath of the Gods TV Anime Trailer |url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2019/08/23/heroes-and-villains-clash-in-the-seven-deadly-sins-wrath-of-the-gods-tv-anime-trailer |website=[[Crunchyroll]] |accessdate=August 24, 2019 |date=August 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823235700/https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2019/08/23/heroes-and-villains-clash-in-the-seven-deadly-sins-wrath-of-the-gods-tv-anime-trailer |archive-date=August 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The new season will be headed towards the story's climax. The third season is animated by [[Studio Deen]] with Susumu Nishizawa and Rintar\u014d Ikeda replacing Takeshi Furuta and Takao Yoshioka as director and series composer, respectively. Hiroyuki Sawano, Kohta Yamamoto, and Takafumi Wada are returning to reprise their roles as the music composers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-04-09/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-gets-fall-tv-show-to-head-toward-climax-with-new-studio/.145546|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Anime Gets Fall TV Show to 'Head Toward Climax' With New Studio|date=April 9, 2019|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=April 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410003059/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-04-09/the-seven-deadly-sins-anime-gets-fall-tv-show-to-head-toward-climax-with-new-studio/.145546|archive-date=April 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monstersandcritics.com/anime/the-seven-deadly-sins-season-4-release-date-confirmed-2019-netflix-u-s-nanatsu-no-taizai-season-3-kamigami-no-gekirin-wrath-of-the-gods-manga-spoilers/|title=The Seven Deadly Sins \u2018Season 4\u2019 release date confirmed for 2019: Nanatsu no Taizai Season 3 called Kamigami no Gekirin (Wrath of the Gods) \u2013 Manga compared to the anime [Spoilers]|date=April 10, 2019|website=[[Monsters and Critics]]|accessdate=April 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410133251/https://www.monstersandcritics.com/anime/the-seven-deadly-sins-season-4-release-date-confirmed-2019-netflix-u-s-nanatsu-no-taizai-season-3-kamigami-no-gekirin-wrath-of-the-gods-manga-spoilers/|archive-date=April 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The first opening theme song is \"ROB THE FRONTIER\" by [[Uverworld]], and the first ending theme song is \"Regeneration\" by Sora Amamiya.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-08-23/uverworld-perform-new-seven-deadly-sins-tv-anime-opening-theme-song/.150358|title=UVERworld Perform New Seven Deadly Sins TV Anime's Opening Theme Song|date=August 23, 2019|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=August 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823175637/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-08-23/uverworld-perform-new-seven-deadly-sins-tv-anime-opening-theme-song/.150358|archive-date=August 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The second opening theme song is \"delete\" by [[Sid (band)|SID]] and the second ending theme is \"Good day\" by Kana Adachi.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Jennifer |title=Sid, Kana Adachi Perform Seven Deadly Sins Anime's New Theme Songs |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-12-19/sid-kana-adachi-perform-seven-deadly-sins-anime-new-theme-songs/.154546 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=December 19, 2019 |date=December 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191219144144/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-12-19/sid-kana-adachi-perform-seven-deadly-sins-anime-new-theme-songs/.154546 |archive-date=December 19, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\u3000\n\nA fourth season, titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Anger's Judgement''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u61a4\u6012\u306e\u5be9\u5224|Nanatsu no Taizai: Fundo no Shinpan}} will premiere in October 2020 on TV Tokyo and BS TV Tokyo, with the main cast members reprising their roles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-24/seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-new-anime-in-october/.157783|title=Seven Deadly Sins Manga Gets New Anime in October|publisher=Anime News Network|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324153622/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-24/seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-new-anime-in-october/.157783|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-25/seven-deadly-sins-anime-ad-teases-lead-up-to-new-series/.157924|title= Seven Deadly Sins Anime Ad Teases Lead-Up to New Series|publisher=Anime News Network|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Original video animation====\nAn [[original video animation]] (OVA) titled {{nihongo|\"Ban's Additional Chapter\"|\u30d0\u30f3\u306e\u756a\u5916\u7de8|Ban no Bangai-hen}} was included with the limited edition of volume 15 of the manga, released on June 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-03-16/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-to-bundle-ova-episode-about-ban/.86033|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga to Bundle OVA Episode About Ban|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-03-16|accessdate=2015-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317002550/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-03-16/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-to-bundle-ova-episode-about-ban/.86033|archive-date=March 17, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A second OVA composed of nine humorous shorts was shipped with the limited edition of the sixteenth volume of the manga, released on August 12, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-11/2nd-seven-deadly-sins-ova-to-compile-9-short-stories/.88041|title=2nd Seven Deadly Sins OVA to Compile 9 Short Stories|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-05-11|accessdate=2015-05-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513204057/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-11/2nd-seven-deadly-sins-ova-to-compile-9-short-stories/.88041|archive-date=May 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\nAn anime film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-07-16/seven-deadly-sins-gets-anime-film-in-summer-2018/.118902|title=Seven Deadly Sins Gets Anime Film in Summer 2018|date=July 16, 2017|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=July 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718125236/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-07-16/seven-deadly-sins-gets-anime-film-in-summer-2018/.118902|archive-date=July 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> titled {{nihongo|''[[The Seven Deadly Sins the Movie: Prisoners of the Sky]]''|\u5287\u5834\u7248 \u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u5929\u7a7a\u306e\u56da\u308f\u308c\u4eba|Gekij\u014d-ban Nanatsu no Taizai Tenk\u016b no Torawarebito}}, premiered in Japanese theaters on August 18, 2018. It is directed by Yasuto Nishikata and written by [[Makoto Uezu]], featuring an original story by [[Nakaba Suzuki]] and [[Noriyuki Abe]] serving as chief director. The other main staff members returned from the anime series to reprise their roles in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-02-15/seven-deadly-sins-film-reveals-teaser-video-visual-august-18-release/.127832|title=Seven Deadly Sins Film Reveals Teaser Video, Visual, August 18 Release|date=February 15, 2018|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=February 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216025545/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-02-15/seven-deadly-sins-film-reveals-teaser-video-visual-august-18-release/.127832|archive-date=February 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The movie features three original characters called Sorada (voiced by [[Tsubasa Yonaga]]), Elatte (voiced by [[Haruka Tomatsu]]), and Bellion (voiced by [[Toshiyuki Morikawa]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://manga.tokyo/news/seven-deadly-sins-movie-reveals-visual-and-more/|title=Seven Deadly Sins Movie Reveals Visual and more|date=April 16, 2018|website=[[MANGA.TOKYO]]|accessdate=April 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416200659/https://manga.tokyo/news/seven-deadly-sins-movie-reveals-visual-and-more/|archive-date=April 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released later by Netflix in all regions on December 31, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-01-01/netflix-adds-pokemon-and-seven-deadly-sins-films/.141539|title=Netflix Adds Pokemon and Seven Deadly Sins Films|date=January 1, 2019|website=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=January 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101194019/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-01-01/netflix-adds-pokemon-and-seven-deadly-sins-films/.141539|archive-date=January 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Video games===\nA video game titled {{nihongo|''Seven Deadly Sins: Unjust Sin''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u771f\u5b9f\u306e\u51a4\u7f6a|Nanatsu no Taizai Shinjitsu no Enzai}} was developed by [[Bandai Namco Entertainment]] and released for the [[Nintendo 3DS]] on February 11, 2015.<ref name=\"5 million\"/> A game titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Knights of Britannia''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u30d6\u30ea\u30bf\u30cb\u30a2\u306e\u65c5\u4eba|Nanatsu no Taizai: Buritania no Tabibito}} was developed by Bandai Namco for the [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nakaba Suzuki's The Seven Deadly Sins Manga Gets PS4 Action Game|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-26/nakaba-suzuki-the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-ps4-action-game/.117996|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=June 26, 2017|date=June 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626134247/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-26/nakaba-suzuki-the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-gets-ps4-action-game/.117996|archive-date=June 26, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in North America and Europe on February 9, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Knights of Britannia PS4 Game Gets U.S. Release in Early 2018|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-07-01/the-seven-deadly-sins-knights-of-britannia-ps4-game-gets-u.s-release-in-early-2018/.118272|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=July 1, 2017|date=July 1, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702021535/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-07-01/the-seven-deadly-sins-knights-of-britannia-ps4-game-gets-u.s-release-in-early-2018/.118272|archive-date=July 2, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Knights of Britannia coming to Europe in early 2018|url=http://gematsu.com/2017/07/seven-deadly-sins-knights-britannia-coming-europe-early-2018|first=Sal|last=Romano|website=Gematsu|date=July 3, 2017|accessdate=July 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703134357/http://gematsu.com/2017/07/seven-deadly-sins-knights-britannia-coming-europe-early-2018|archive-date=July 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> A mobile game titled {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Grand Cross of Light and Darkness''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u5149\u3068\u95c7\u306e\u4ea4\u6226|Nanatsu no Taizai Hikari to Yami no Gurando Kurosu}} was developed by [[Netmarble]] and released in Japan and Korea in June 4, 2019. On March 3, the game was released globally for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Seven Deadly Sins: Grand Cross Launches Globally on March 3|url=https://whatoplay.com/news/seven-deadly-sins-grand-cross-global-release/|first=Pia |last=Aguilos|website=whatoplay|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n===Other media===\nFour [[light novel]]s based on ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' have been published; {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins -Gaiden- The Seven Wishes of the Royal City from Old Times''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u2015\u5916\u4f1d\u2015\u3000\u6614\u65e5\u306e\u738b\u90fd\u3000\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u9858\u3044|Nanatsu no Taizai -Gaiden- Sekijitsu no \u014cto Nanatsu no Negai}} by Shuka Matsuda on December 17, 2014; {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Seven Days''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u30bb\u30d6\u30f3\u30c7\u30a4\u30ba|Nanatsu no Taizai Sebun Deizu}} by Mamoru Iwasa on December 26, 2014; {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Seven Scars They Left Behind''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u2015\u5916\u4f1d\u2015\u3000\u5f7c\u3089\u304c\u6b8b\u3057\u305f\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u50b7\u8de1|Nanatsu no Taizai -Gaiden- Karera ga Nokoshita Nanatsu no Kizuato}} by Shuka Matsuda on October 16, 2015; and {{nihongo|''The Seven Deadly Sins: Seven-Colored Recollections''|\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a \u2015\u5916\u4f1d\u2015 \u4e03\u8272\u306e\u8ffd\u61b6|Nanatsu no Taizai -Gaiden- Nanairo no Tsuioku}} by Shuka Matsuda on October 17, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771060|script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u8aac\u3000\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u2015\u5916\u4f1d\u2015\u3000\u6614\u65e5\u306e\u738b\u90fd\u3000\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u9858\u3044|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2015-06-29|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413111548/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771060|archive-date=April 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063753929|script-title=ja:\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u30bb\u30d6\u30f3\u30c7\u30a4\u30ba|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2014-06-29|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413092559/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063753929|archive-date=April 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063772982|script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u8aac\u3000\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u2015\u5916\u4f1d\u2015\u3000\u5f7c\u3089\u304c\u6b8b\u3057\u305f\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u50b7\u8de1|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2015-12-01|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208063409/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063772982|archive-date=December 8, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063930542|script-title=ja:\u5c0f\u8aac\u3000\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u2015\u5916\u4f1d\u2015\u3000\u4e03\u8272\u306e\u8ffd\u61b6|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2018-02-05|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205133241/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063930542|archive-date=February 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vertical (company)|Vertical]] released ''Seven Scars They Left Behind'' in North America in May 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-08-13/vertical-to-release-the-seven-deadly-sins-the-seven-scars-left-behind-novel/.105345 |title=Vertical to Release The Seven Deadly Sins: The Seven Scars Left Behind Novel |website=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2016-08-13 |accessdate=2016-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815025632/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-08-13/vertical-to-release-the-seven-deadly-sins-the-seven-scars-left-behind-novel/.105345 |archive-date=August 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> with ''Seven-Colored Recollections'' set to follow in March 2018.\n\nAn illustration collection titled {{nihongo|''Rainbow of Sin''|\u4e03\u8272\u306e\u7f6a|Nanairo no Tsumi}} and an official fan book were both released on February 17, 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771589|script-title=ja:\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u30a4\u30e9\u30b9\u30c8\u30b3\u30ec\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u3000\u3008\u4e03\u8272\u306e\u7f6a\u3009|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2014-06-29|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220150223/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771589|archive-date=February 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771312|script-title=ja:\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u516c\u5f0f\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u3000\u89e3\u4f53\u7f6a\u66f8|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2014-06-29|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413062507/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771312|archive-date=April 13, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> while a guidebook for the anime called {{nihongo|''Ani-Sin''|\u30a2\u30cb\u7f6a|Ani-Tsumi}} was released on April 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771749|script-title=ja:\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u3000\u516c\u5f0f\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u30ac\u30a4\u30c9\u3000\u30a2\u30cb\u7f6a|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|accessdate=2014-06-29|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422044321/http://kc.kodansha.co.jp/product?isbn=9784063771749|archive-date=April 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAs of August 2014, the collected volumes of ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' had 5 million copies in circulation.<ref name=\"5 million\"/> By January 2015, this number had grown to 10 million sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-19/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-1st-of-3-planned-arcs-ends/.83434|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga's 1st of 3 Planned Arcs Ends|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-01-19|accessdate=2015-01-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119110059/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-19/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-1st-of-3-planned-arcs-ends/.83434|archive-date=January 19, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> As of June 2018, the series has 28 million copies in circulation,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000002.000034196.html | title=\u300c\u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\u300d\u9234\u6728\u592e\u5148\u751f\u63cf\u304d\u4e0b\u308d\u3057\u306e\u30aa\u30ea\u30b8\u30ca\u30eb\u30b9\u30c8\u30fc\u30ea\u30fc\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u4ed8\u304d\uff01 | date=2018-06-15 | publisher=PR Times | accessdate=2018-08-08 | language=Japanese | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180808233952/https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000002.000034196.html | archive-date=August 8, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and over 30 million copies in circulation as of December 2018.<ref name=\"dec18\">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-02/roundup-of-newly-revealed-print-counts-for-manga-light-novel-series-november-2018/.139661|title=Roundup of Newly Revealed Print Counts for Manga, Light Novel Series - November 2018|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2018-12-02|accessdate=2018-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181203194819/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-12-02/roundup-of-newly-revealed-print-counts-for-manga-light-novel-series-november-2018/.139661|archive-date=December 3, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The first collected volume of the series sold 38,581 copies in its first week, ranking number 13 on the [[Oricon]] manga chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-02-20/japanese-comic-ranking-february-11-17|title=Japanese Comic Ranking, February 11\u201317|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-02-20|accessdate=2013-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014064502/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-02-20/japanese-comic-ranking-february-11-17|archive-date=October 14, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Its second volume ranked 5 selling 106,829 in its first week,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-04-24/japanese-comic-ranking-april-14-20|title=Japanese Comic Ranking, April 15\u201321|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-04-24|accessdate=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824180318/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-04-24/japanese-comic-ranking-april-14-20|archive-date=August 24, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> while its third debuted at number 4 with 135,164 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-06-26/japanese-comic-ranking-june-16-22|title=Japanese Comic Ranking, June 17\u201323|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-06-26|accessdate=2013-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130831230238/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-06-26/japanese-comic-ranking-june-16-22|archive-date=August 31, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The thirteenth volume had the manga's best debut week to date, selling 442,492 for first place on the chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-02-25/japanese-comic-ranking-february-16-22/.85394|title=Japanese Comic Ranking, February 16\u201322|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-02-25|accessdate=2015-05-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203130317/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-02-25/japanese-comic-ranking-february-16-22/.85394|archive-date=December 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The series was the ninth best-selling manga of 2014, with over 4.6 million copies sold that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-30/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2014/.81607|title=Top-Selling Manga in Japan by Series: 2014|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-11-30|accessdate=2014-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327092207/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-11-30/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2014/.81607|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> For the first half of 2015, ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' was the number one best-selling series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-31/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2015/.88770|title=Top-Selling Manga in Japan by Series: 2015 (First Half)|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-05-31|accessdate=2015-06-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150601235353/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-31/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2015/.88770|archive-date=June 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It finished the year in second place with over 10.3 million copies sold, behind only ''[[One Piece]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-11-29/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2015/.95913|title=Top-Selling Manga in Japan by Series: 2015|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-11-29|accessdate=2015-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504033522/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-11-29/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2015/.95913|archive-date=May 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the sixth best-selling of 2016, with over 5 million copies sold, and the seventh of 2017, with close to 3.6 million copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-11-30/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2016/.109352|title=Top-Selling Manga in Japan by Series: 2016|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2016-11-30|accessdate=2016-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221103619/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-11-30/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2016/.109352|archive-date=December 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-12-06/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2017/.124894|title=Top-Selling Manga in Japan by Series: 2017|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2017-12-06|accessdate=2017-12-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701194925/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-12-06/top-selling-manga-in-japan-by-series-2017/.124894|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The 2014 edition of ''[[Kono Manga ga Sugoi!]]'', which surveys people in the manga and publishing industry, named ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' the fifth best manga series for male readers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-12-09/top-manga-ranked-by-kono-manga-ga-sugoi-2014-voters|title=Top Manga Ranked by Kono Manga ga Sugoi 2014 Voters|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-12-09|accessdate=2013-12-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508113757/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-12-09/top-manga-ranked-by-kono-manga-ga-sugoi-2014-voters|archive-date=May 8, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The title was named Best Sh\u014dnen Manga at the 39th [[Kodansha Manga Awards]] alongside ''[[Yowamushi Pedal]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-12/yowamushi-pedal-the-seven-deadly-sins-win-39th-kodansha-manga-awards/.88088|title=Yowamushi Pedal, The Seven Deadly Sins Win 39th Kodansha Manga Awards|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-05-12|accessdate=2015-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515021417/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-05-12/yowamushi-pedal-the-seven-deadly-sins-win-39th-kodansha-manga-awards/.88088|archive-date=May 15, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also nominated for the 2014 [[Manga Taish\u014d]] award and as Best Youth Comic at the 42nd [[Angoul\u00eame International Comics Festival]] in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-01-20/10-titles-nominated-for-7th-manga-taisho-awards|title=10 Titles Nominated for 7th Manga Taisho Awards|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-01-20|accessdate=2014-01-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606051838/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-01-20/10-titles-nominated-for-7th-manga-taisho-awards|archive-date=June 6, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-29/akira-katsuhiro-otomo-wins-angouleme-top-prize/.83854|title=Akira's Katsuhiro Otomo Wins Angoul\u00eame's Top Prize|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-01-29|accessdate=2015-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201061455/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-29/akira-katsuhiro-otomo-wins-angouleme-top-prize/.83854|archive-date=February 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe North American releases of volumes two and four charted on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times Manga Best Seller'' list]] at number seven and nine respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-05-23/new-york-times-manga-best-seller-list-may-11-17/.74856 |title=New York Times Manga Best Seller List, May 11\u201317 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2014-05-23 |accessdate=2014-05-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524074213/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-05-23/new-york-times-manga-best-seller-list-may-11-17/.74856 |archive-date=May 24, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-09-26/new-york-times-manga-best-seller-list-september-14-20/.79252 |title=New York Times Manga Best Seller List, September 14\u201320 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2014-09-26 |accessdate=2014-09-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927033900/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-09-26/new-york-times-manga-best-seller-list-september-14-20/.79252 |archive-date=September 27, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Rebecca Silverman of [[Anime News Network]] (ANN) gave the first volume a B grade, calling the art interesting and the story a \"neat take on the basic knights-in-shining-armor.\" She saw influence from [[Akira Toriyama]] in Meliodas and 1970s [[sh\u014djo manga|''sh\u014djo'' manga]] in the female characters. However, Silverman felt the art had issues with [[Perspective (visual)|perspective]] and commented that Elizabeth lacked character development.<ref name=\"Silverman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/the-seven-deadly-sins/gn-1|title=The Seven Deadly Sins GN 1 - Review|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2014-05-15|accessdate=2014-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140619053527/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/the-seven-deadly-sins/gn-1|archive-date=June 19, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Both Silverman and Danica Davidson of ''[[Otaku USA]]'' warned that Meliodas' perverted actions towards Elizabeth, which are used for comedic relief, could possibly be misinterpreted by some readers.<ref name=\"Silverman\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.otakuusamagazine.com/Manga/News1/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Manga-1-5606.aspx|title=The Seven Deadly Sins Manga #1|publisher=[[Otaku USA]]|date=2014-04-14|accessdate=2014-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723075544/http://otakuusamagazine.com/Manga/News1/The-Seven-Deadly-Sins-Manga-1-5606.aspx|archive-date=July 23, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In a brief review, [[Jason Thompson (writer)|Jason Thompson]] claimed that the series follows common [[sh\u014dnen manga|''sh\u014dnen'' manga]] elements, making its plot twists and dialog predictable. He did however like the art and the series' European setting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/house-of-1000-manga/2013-11-14|title=House of 1000 Manga - Crunchyroll Manga|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2013-11-14|accessdate=2013-11-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222002301/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/house-of-1000-manga/2013-11-14|archive-date=December 22, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe first DVD volume of the anime debuted at number one on Oricon's Japanese animation DVD chart with 3,574 copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-02-03/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-january-26-february-1/.84030|title=Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, January 26-February 1|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-02-03|accessdate=2015-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702102756/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-02-03/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-january-26-february-1/.84030|archive-date=July 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> With 32,762 copies sold of the five volumes released at the time, ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' was the 30th best-selling anime of the first half of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-06-17/top-selling-animation-in-japan-by-title-2015/.89373|title=Top-Selling Animation in Japan by Title: 2015 (First Half)|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-06-17|accessdate=2015-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704201543/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-06-17/top-selling-animation-in-japan-by-title-2015/.89373|archive-date=July 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Reviewing the first anime for ANN, Theron Martin felt that the series has a slow start with generic ''sh\u014dnen'' action fare but the storytelling picks up significantly in the second half. He had strong praise for the music and enjoyed the main cast and their interactions, but not the common archetypal villains. Martin noted that the art has a \"semi-cartoonish look\" that one would expect in a series that \"skews a bit younger,\" but ''The Seven Deadly Sins''{{'}} graphic violence and minimal [[fan service]] prove its \"anything but a kiddie show.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/the-seven-deadly-sins/episodes-1-24/.95395|title=The Seven Deadly Sins - Review|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-11-20|accessdate=2017-02-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227062701/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/the-seven-deadly-sins/episodes-1-24/.95395|archive-date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe novel ''The Seven Deadly Sins -Gaiden- Sekijitsu no \u014cto Nanatsu no Negai'' was the 33rd best-selling light novel of the first half of 2015, with 61,939 copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-06-02/top-selling-light-novels-in-japan-by-volume-2015/.88814|title=Top-Selling Light Novels in Japan by Volume: 2015 (First Half)|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2015-06-02|accessdate=2015-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705155044/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-06-02/top-selling-light-novels-in-japan-by-volume-2015/.88814|archive-date=July 5, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Netflix revealed that ''The Seven Deadly Sins'' anime was the fourth most [[binge-watch]]ed show within its first 24 hours of release on their platform.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ready, Set, Binge: More Than 8 Million Viewers 'Binge Race' Their Favorite Series |url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/ready-set-binge-more-than-8-million-viewers-binge-race-their-favorite-series |accessdate=1 March 2019 |work=[[Netflix Media Center]] |publisher=[[Netflix]] |date=17 October 2017 |language=en |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6uQ0HpHpE?url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/ready-set-binge-more-than-8-million-viewers-binge-race-their-favorite-series |archive-date=October 23, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shonenmagazine.com/smaga/nanatsunotaizai Official page at ''Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine'']\n*[http://www.7-taizai.net/ Official anime website]\n*[http://7ds.bngames.net/ Official video game website]\n*{{ann|manga|15698|The Seven Deadly Sins}}\n\n{{The Seven Deadly Sins}}\n{{Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine - 2010\u20132019}}\n{{Kodansha Manga Award - Sh\u014dnen}}\n{{Seven Deadly Sins}}\n{{A-1 Pictures}}\n{{Studio Deen}}\n{{Nichigo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seven Deadly Sins}}\n[[Category:2014 Japanese television series debuts]]\n[[Category:A-1 Pictures]]\n[[Category:Adventure anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Anime composed by Hiroyuki Sawano]]\n[[Category:Anime OVAs composed by Hiroyuki Sawano]]\n[[Category:Aniplex]]\n[[Category:Fantasy anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Funimation]]\n[[Category:Kodansha manga]]\n[[Category:Mainichi Broadcasting System shows]]\n[[Category:Netflix original anime]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Makoto Uezu]]\n[[Category:The Seven Deadly Sins]]\n[[Category:Sh\u014dnen manga]]\n[[Category:Studio Deen]]\n[[Category:TV Tokyo shows]]\n[[Category:Vertical (company) titles]]\n[[Category:Winner of Kodansha Manga Award (Sh\u014dnen)]]\n[[Category:Seven deadly sins in popular culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Nanatsu no Taizai|Hobby Japan's media franchise of the same name|Seven Mortal Sins}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = Seven Deadly Sins\n| image           = Nanatsu no Taizai Volume 1.png\n| caption         = First volume of ''The Seven Deadly Sins'', released in Japan by [[Kodansha]] featuring Elizabeth Liones (left), Meliodas (center) and Hawk (right).\n| ja_kanji        = \u4e03\u3064\u306e\u5927\u7f6a\n| ja_romaji       = Nanatsu no Taizai\n| genre           = [[Adventure fiction|Adventure]], [[fantasy]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Davidson |first1=Danica |title=The Seven Deadly Sins #1 [Manga Review] |url=https://www.otakuusamagazine.com/the-seven-deadly-sins-manga-review-1/ |website=[[Otaku USA]] |accessdate=January 9, 2020 |date=April 14, 2014 |quote=The Seven Deadly Sins starts out as a fun, light adventure fantasy.}}</ref><!-- Genres should be based on what reliable sources list them as and not on personal interpretations. Limit of the three most relevant genres in accordance with [[MOS:A&M]]. -->\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| author          = [[Nakaba Suzuki]]\n| publisher       = [[Kodansha]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English manga publisher\n  | NA = {{ubl|[[Kodansha USA]]|[[Crunchyroll]] {{small|(digital)}}}}\n}}\n| demographic     = ''[[Sh\u014dnen manga|Sh\u014dnen]]''\n| imprint         = \n| magazine        = [[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Magazine]]\n| magazine_en     = \n| first           = October 10, 2012\n| last            = March 25, 2020\n| volumes         = 41\n| volume_list     = List of The Seven Deadly Sins chapters\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| title           = Mayoe! The Seven Deadly Sins Academy!\n| type            = manga\n| author          = Juichi Yamaki\n| publisher       = Kodansha\n| publisher_en    = \n| demographic     = ''Sh\u014dnen''\n| imprint         = \n| magazine        = [[Bessatsu Sh\u014dnen Magazine]]\n| magazine_en     = \n| first           = August 9, 2014\n| last            = October 8, 2016\n| volumes         = 4\n| volume_list     = List of The Seven Deadly Sins chapters#Mayoe! The Seven Deadly Sins Academy!\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Video\n| type         = tv series\n| director     = [[Tensai Okamura]]\n| producer     = \n| writer       = Sh\u014dtar\u014d Suga\n| music        = {{ubl|[[Hiroyuki Sawano]]|Takafumi Wada}}\n| studio       = [[A-1 Pictures]]\n| licensee     = {{ubl|[[Netflix]] {{small|(streaming rights)}}|[[Funimation]] {{small|(home video rights)}}}}\n| network      = [[Japan News Network|JNN]] ([[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]], [[Tokyo Broadcasting System|TBS]])\n| network_en   = {{English anime network|SEA=[[Animax Asia]]}}\n| first        = October 5, 2014\n| last         = March 29, 2015\n| episodes     = 24 + 2 OVA\n| episode_list = The Seven Deadly Sins (2014 TV series)\n}